    "updated_at": "2025-08-11T19:38:26Z",
    "body": "That definitely does something! For me it does the opposite even:\n\n```\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ gix status\n 21:36:11 status done 16.0 files in 0.00s (17.9K files/s)\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ git read-tree @\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ gix status\n 21:36:26 status done 16.0 files in 0.00s (7.0K files/s)\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ git status\nOn branch gitbutler/workspace\nUntracked files:\n  (use \"git add <file>...\" to include in what will be committed)\n        Space 📹Ümlaut\n\nnothing added to commit but untracked files present (use \"git add\" to track)\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ rm .git/index\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) -99 [$✘?]\n❯ git read-tree HEAD\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ gst\nOn branch gitbutler/workspace\nUntracked files:\n  (use \"git add <file>...\" to include in what will be committed)\n        Space 📹Ümlaut\n\nnothing added to commit but untracked files present (use \"git add\" to track)\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n❯ gix status\n 21:36:42 status done 16.0 files in 0.00s (16.7K files/s)\n\nsmall ( gitbutler/workspace) [$]\n```\n\nI did, however, use `gitoxide` to create the tree in question, so it's likely that it's now permanently wrong for Git which is of course pretty bad.\n\nThis has to be fixed asap (but I don't know when I get to it).",
